              {
                "id": 2,
                "sequence": 1,
                "body": "The term “quality” as applied to a drug product has been defined as the sum of all factors which contribute directly or indirectly to the safety, effectiveness, and reliability of the product. These properties are built into drug products through research and during the manufacturing process by procedures collectively referred to as “quality control”. Quality control guarantees within reasonable limits that a drug product (1) is free of impurities, (2) is physically and chemically stable, (3) contains the amount of active ingredient(s) as stated on the label, and (4) provides optimal release of active ingredient(s) when the product is administered. Of the four properties listed, item 3 is usually emphasized in quantitative pharmaceutical chemistry. The others are generally considered in other courses of the curriculum. \r\n Standards for drug quality are set by both state and federal agencies. At the federal level drug-quality requirements are set through an organization known as the United States Pharmacopeia Convention, inc., a nonprofit corporation composed of representatives from all accredited colleges and schools of pharmacy and medicine in the country, every state pharmaceutical and medical association and many other national associations such as the American Pharmaceutical Association and the American Medical Association, and various department of the federal government. Drugs are selected for inclusion in a particular revision by a committee composed of medical experts throughout the country. Drug-quality standards for these drugs are then set by medical and pharmaceutical scientists of many disciplines, who represent educational institutions, the federal government, and industry.",
                "caption": "",
