                "id": 3,
                "sequence": 1,
                "body": "Quantitative Pharmaceutical Chemistry may be define as the application of the procedures analytical chemistry (1) to the analysis and determination of the purity and quality of drugs and chemicals used in pharmacy, especially those official in the United States pharmacopeia and the National Formulary (2) to the analysis of the chemical constituents found in the human body whose altered concentrations during disease  states serve as diagnostic aids in the practice of medicine, and (3) to the analysis of medicinal agents and their metabolites found in biological systems.\r\n               In modern practice of pharmacy it is important that pharmacists have more than an appreciation for quantitative analytical methodology. They must have working knowledge if they are to advise medical practitioners on drug quality of a drug product is challenged by a physician, the pharmacist is responsible for initiating steps to determine if indeed the product is defective. This may be accomplished by (1) calling and advising the drug manufacturer of the problem involving the product, (2) analyzing the preparation in the prescription laboratory, borrowing needed equipment from a clinical laboratory if necessary, (3) sending a portion of the sample to a private laboratory for analysis, or (4) a combination of all these steps. In any case, however, it remains the responsibility of the pharmacist to solve problems relating to drug quality. Pharmacist who have reason to believe that a drug product is not a proper quality and appears to be defective, because of improper labeling, discoloration, the presence of cloudiness, crystal, or precipitates in products known to be solutions, or for any other reason, are urged by the Food and Drug Administration and by the nonprofit standards-setting organization, The United States Pharmacopeia, to participate in the Drug Defect Reporting Program by preparing a report, or by completing a form [FD Form 2519a (2/72)], and sending it to: The united States Pharmacopeia, 12601 Twin brook parkway, Rockville, Md. The following information is requested: (1) trade name, dosage form, and strength, (2) lot number(s), (3) date purchased (if known), (4) source of product (where purchased, if known), (5) name address of pharmacy (included ZIP code, (8) telephone number (include area code), and (9) defects noted and suspected. This program alerts manufacturers to defective drug products and thereby ensures better quality in pharmaceutical products for the patient.",
