              {
                "id": 10,
                "sequence": 4,
                "body": "Definitions\r\nThe gram-equivalent weight (GEW) or, more simply, the gram-equivalent of a chemical is defined as that weight in grams which is chemically equivalent to 1 gram-atom of hydrogen (1.0079 g). In neutralization reactions it is defined as that weight of a substance in rams which (1) contains, (2) furnishes, (3) reacts with directly or indirectly, or (4) replaces 1 gram-atom or ion of hydrogen. Gram-milliequivalent weight (GmEW) is defined as GEW/1000. This term is used quite frequently in titrimetric calculations. The term equivalent (equiv) is defined as the number of gram-equivalents involved in a quantitative procedure. The term milliequivalent (meq)is used more frequently and is defined as the number of gram-milliequivalents involved in a quantitative procedure. (A useful analogy to help distinguish between equivalents and gram-equivalent weight is a bag containing identical marbles. The number of marbles in the bag is analogous to the number of gram-equivalents of chemical in solution, and the weight of a single marble is analogous to the gram-equivalent weight of the chemical.) A standard solution is a solution of known normality or molarity. Normality  is a concentration expression and is defined as the number of equivalents of solute per liter (equiv/liter) or milliequivalents per milliliter (meq/ml) of solution. Molarity is an expressions of the concentration of a solution in terms of moles per liter. The determination of the normality or molarity of a solution is known as standardization. This may be accomplished by the use of another standard solution known as a secondary standard, or by the use of a carefully weighed sample of a substance of known purity which is termed a primary standard. Thus a solution of hydrochloric acid may be standardized titrimetrically using a standard solution of sodium hydroxide as a secondary standard or using a sample of sodium carbonate of known purity as a primary standard.",
