                "body": "Quantitative analyses of crude drugs and of the products derived from them are made to established purity or to determine the amount of therapeutically active constituents present for the purpose of standardized. The special methods employed in the analyses of this type may be classified as follows:\r\n               Chemical methods, such as those employed in the determination of ash, moisture, crude fiber, extractive obtained with different solvents, the estimation of alkaloidal content, etc.\r\n               Biological methods or those in which the affects of drugs upon microbes, animals, or animal tissues are measured and which are employed in the absence of satisfactory chemical methods for standardization. Official standards for drugs or preparations include biological assays or tests for such medicinal agents as adrenal cortex, corticotrophin, digitalis, heparin sodium, insulin, oxytocin, parathyroid, and vasopressin. Microbiological assays are required for antibiotics, liver, vitamin B 1 and 2, and other related drugs. Tests are required for the toxicity and potency of serological preparations such as vaccines, serums, toxoids, and antitoxins. Biological methods required special apparatus for their performance and a technique that is not chemical in nature; hence a discussion of them does not fall within the scope of this text.\r\nMany tests of antibiotics which are based on chemical reactions are no longer included in the official compendiums, because they are available in the Federal Register. All antibiotics intended for use in humans are subject to production and testing controls under federal regulations. The Food and Drug Administration publishes these regulations in the Federal Register, and all the antibiotics recognized in the official compendiums are subject to the provisions of these regulations. Therefore analytical methods for the determination of purity, moisture, and other constants are obtained from this publication.